    <h3 style="font-family:'Cinzel Decorative',serif;color:var(--gold);font-size:16px;margin:40px 0 20px;padding-bottom:12px;border-bottom:1px solid var(--border)">
      The Real Bombshell ‚Äî The False Prophet IS the Dajjal-Elijah Connection
    </h3>

    <div class="callout">
      <strong>Revelation 13:13</strong> says the False Prophet (second beast) "performed great signs, even <em>causing fire to come down from heaven</em>." Calling fire from heaven is <strong>Elijah's signature miracle</strong> ‚Äî no other Biblical figure is specifically associated with it. This suggests the False Prophet is an <strong>Elijah-impersonator</strong> ‚Äî a counterfeit Elijah who performs the real Elijah's miracles in service of the Antichrist.
    </div>

    <div class="three-cols" style="margin-top:30px">
      <div class="lens-card theologian">
        <div class="lens-icon">üî•</div>
        <h3>The Counterfeit Elijah Reading</h3>
        <p>Satan always counterfeits God's plan. The real Elijah (Two Witnesses) returns to call people to repent. Satan sends a Counterfeit Elijah (False Prophet / Dajjal) who performs the same miracles ‚Äî fire from heaven, control of rain ‚Äî to deceive people into following the Antichrist (Mahdi).</p>
        <p>Under the inversion thesis: The real Two Witnesses (Elijah+Moses) are the ones the Islamic world calls Dajjal's associates or enemies. The counterfeit Elijah (Islamic Isa who performs signs) is what the Bible calls the False Prophet.</p>
        <div class="verdict-line">
          <div class="verdict-dot" style="background:var(--gold)"></div>
          <span style="color:var(--gold)">Most theologically coherent mapping</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lens-card islamic-scholar">
        <div class="lens-icon">‚òΩ</div>
        <h3>Islamic Response</h3>
        <p>From an Islamic perspective, Elijah (Ilyas) is a respected prophet mentioned in the Quran (6:85, 37:123-132). He is not identified with Dajjal ‚Äî quite the opposite. The Dajjal is the enemy of all prophets.</p>
        <p>However, the Islamic framework does warn that the Dajjal will perform convincing miracles that will deceive even the faithful. A figure appearing with miraculous signs who claims prophetic authority would fit what Islam warns people to reject.</p>
        <div class="verdict-line">
          <div class="verdict-dot" style="background:var(--danger)"></div>
          <span style="color:var(--danger)">Rejected ‚Äî Ilyas/Elijah is honored in Islam</span>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="lens-card secular">
        <div class="lens-icon">üî≠</div>
        <h3>Secular Analysis</h3>
        <p>The fire-from-heaven miracle shared by Elijah, the Two Witnesses, and the False Prophet suggests a common mythological archetype of the thunder-prophet ‚Äî a figure who commands divine fire. This appears in Zoroastrian (Ahura Mazda), Greek (Zeus), and Semitic traditions.</p>
        <p>The Dajjal's imprisonment-before-emergence parallels Elijah's translation to heaven ‚Äî both involve figures who exit normal history and return at a critical moment. Whether this reflects prophetic identity or archetypal storytelling is the irreducible question.</p>
        <div class="verdict-line">
          <div class="verdict-dot" style="background:var(--gold)"></div>
          <span style="color:var(--gold)">Interesting archetype ‚Äî unprovable as identity</spa